    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                          17,57
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,18
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          82,43
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           4,90
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,39
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 5.7 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to     
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          4.90 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.39 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,18
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    32,00
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        29,54
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 13.5 cycles being stalled waiting after an EXIT instruction for    
          all outstanding memory instructions to complete so that the warp's resources can be freed. This represents    
          about 48.5% of the total average of 27.9 cycles between issuing two instructions. A high number of stalls     
          due to draining warps typically occurs when a lot of data is written to memory towards the end of a kernel.   
          Make sure the memory access patterns of these store operations are optimal for the target architecture and    
          consider parallelized data reduction, if applicable.

    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           9,35
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,09
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          90,65
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           5,61
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,15
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 10.7 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          5.61 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.15 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           6,39
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,13
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 8.5 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to     
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          6.39 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.13 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    12,90
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        12,81
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 45.2 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 83.0% of the total average of 54.5   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 12.9 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 12.8 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           6,22
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 35.4 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          6.22 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    13,80
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        12,87
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 211.6 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on  
          a L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 96.1% of the total average of      
          220.2 cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses  
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 13.8 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 12.9 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 39.5 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          7.64 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 40.4 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    17,32
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        16,11
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 34.8 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 43.2% of the total average of 80.6 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 32.1 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 39.9% of the total average of 80.6   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 17.3 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 16.1 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 37.5 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------

    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,14
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    13,83
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        12,96
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 27.3 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 36.4% of the total average of 75.1 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 30.7 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 40.8% of the total average of 75.1   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 13.8 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 13.0 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,78
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,22
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 36.0 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------

    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,20
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    12,80
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        12,22
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 41.0 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 56.9% of the total average of 72.1 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 12.8 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 12.2 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,49
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,02
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,51
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 40.2 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------

    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           4,41
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00

    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,49
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,06
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00

    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,29
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,02
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    15,01
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        14,37
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 53.0 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 66.0% of the total average of 80.3 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 15.0 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 14.4 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,48
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,02
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,52
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 40.3 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          80,60
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          85,37
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          80,60
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          55,81

    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                          12,45
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,01
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           4,48
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,10
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,51
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,07
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           0,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,35
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,02
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    16,19
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        15,53
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 55.8 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 69.2% of the total average of 80.6 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 16.2 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 15.5 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,52
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,48
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 39.7 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          79,32

    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           4,48
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00

    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,51
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,07
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,38
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    16,62
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        15,95
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 55.3 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 69.7% of the total average of 79.3 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 16.6 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 16.0 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,57
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,43
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 39.0 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------

    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,07
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,40
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    17,00
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        16,31
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 54.1 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 69.2% of the total average of 78.2 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 17.0 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 16.3 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,64
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,36
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 37.9 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          75,66

    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          75,66
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          52,04

    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           4,59
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,10
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,52
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,08
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00

    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,39
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    17,47
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        16,76
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 52.0 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 68.8% of the total average of 75.7 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 17.5 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 16.8 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,71
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,29
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,01
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 36.9 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.01 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          73,97
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          77,91
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          73,97
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          50,19

    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                          11,11
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,01
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           4,73
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,10
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,53
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,08
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           0,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,40
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    17,95
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        17,24
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 50.2 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 67.9% of the total average of 74.0 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 18.0 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 17.2 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,78
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,22
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 36.0 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          71,77
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          75,38
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          71,77
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          47,84

    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           0,04

    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                          11,20
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,01
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           4,89
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,09
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,53
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,08
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           0,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,39
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    18,48
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        17,74
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 47.8 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 66.7% of the total average of 71.8 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 18.5 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 17.7 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           2,84
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,03
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          97,16
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,00
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 35.2 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.00 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.03 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          70,24
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          73,73
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          70,24
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          45,89
    Stall Dispatch Stall                                                              inst                           0,00
    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,00
    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           0,04
    Stall LG Throttle                                                                 inst                              0
    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                          11,28
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,01
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                           5,03
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,09
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,54
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,08
    Selected                                                                          inst                           1,00
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           0,11
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           3,38
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,03
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    18,92
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        18,16
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 45.9 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 65.3% of the total average of 70.2 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 18.9 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 18.2 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.
